                <li><a href="#">WHO CAN GIVE BLOOD</a>
                <div class="sub-menu-1">
                <ul>
                <h3>WHO CAN GIVE BlOOD</h3>
                Most people can give blood if they are in good health. There are some basic requirements one <br> 
               need to fulfill in order to become a blood donor. Below are some basic eligibility guidelines:<br>

                <h3>Age:</h3>
                (1)You are aged between 18 and 65.<br>

                (2)In some countries national legislation permits 16–17 year-olds to donate provided that they<br>
                fulfil the physical and hematological criteria required and that appropriate consent is obtained.<br>
                (3)In some countries, regular donors over the age of 65 may be accepted at the discretion of the <br>
                (4)responsible physician. The upper age limit in some countries are 60. <br>
                <h3>Weight:</h3>
                (1)You weigh at least 50 kg.<br>    

                (2)In some countries, donors of whole blood donations should weigh at least 45 kg to donate 350 ml ± 10%.
                Health :<br>    
                (1)You must be in good health at the time you donate.<br>
                (2)You must not donate blood If you do not meet the minimum haemoglobin level for blood donation:<br>
                (3)A test will be administered at the donation site. In many countries, a haemoglobin level of not less<br> than 12.0 g/dl for females and not less than 13.0 g/dl for males as the threshold.
                Travel.<br>
                (1)Many countries also implemented the policy to defer blood donors with a history of travel or residence for<br> defined cumulative exposure periods in specified countries or areas, as a measure to reduce the risk of transmitting <br>variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD) by blood transfusion.<br>

                <h3>Behaviours:</h3>
                (1)You must not give blood:<br>

                (1)If you engaged in “at risk” sexual activity in the past 12 months.<br>
                (2)Individuals with behaviours below will be deferred permanently: <br>
                (3)Have ever had a positive test for HIV (AIDS virus)<br>
                (4)Have ever injected recreational drugs.<br>
            </ul>
        </div>
